# Lab Name
DOM XSS in document.write sink using source location.search inside a select element

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – DOM-Based XSS

## Objective
Exploit a DOM-based XSS vulnerability and execute JavaScript in the browser.

## Entry Point
URL query string (location.search)

## Exploitation Type
DOM-Based XSS

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and inspect the page source

2. Observe that user input is taken from:

   location.search

3. Notice that the value is written to the page using:

   document.write()

4. The input is inserted inside a select element

5. Since the application does not properly sanitize user input, it is possible to break out of the select context

6. Inject a payload that closes the current element and introduces an element containing a JavaScript event

7. Append the payload to the URL parameter

8. Load the page

9. Observe that the JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

</select><img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>

## Result
Successfully executed arbitrary JavaScript through a DOM-based XSS vulnerability.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise
- Manipulation of page content

## Mitigation
- Avoid using document.write() with untrusted data
- Sanitize and validate all user-controlled input
- Use safe DOM manipulation methods such as textContent
- Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Perform proper output encoding

## Learning
DOM-based XSS can occur when user-controlled data is inserted into the DOM without proper sanitization.
Even when input is placed inside specific HTML elements such as select tags, attackers may escape the context and inject executable content.
